PI doesn't provide them. System-level testing with the actual API is required.\n\nUsing the key questions: the behavior involves multiple modules interacting (STT and summarization), and it depends on real network calls to the STT API. Both factors point to System testing as the minimum level needed to catch this failure mode.\n\nFor behavior 2, the core issue is the LLM's judgment in extracting action items and attributing them to specific attendees. Mocking the LLM would hide real failures where it misses items or assigns them incorrectly. Since correctness depends entirely on what the real model produces, this requires Agentic-level testing. Behavior 3 follows the same pattern—the LLM's ability to properly categorize decisions into the correct section depends on the actual model's output, not on code logic, so it also needs Agentic testing.\n\nFor behavior 4, handling long audio files involves multiple failure modes. The service needs to split files correctly (testable at Unit/Integration level), but also needs the real STT API to process segments without hitting limits or producing inconsistent results compared to full-file processing. Additionally, the LLM must coherently merge the transcribed segments back together. Mocking the STT API would mask real API constraints, and the merging quality depends on the LLM's actual capabilities, so this requires both real infrastructure and Agentic-level testing. APIs and the LLM's ability to merge transcripts coherently. The STT component requires real API calls to handle segmented audio properly, while the merging quality depends on actual LLM processing. Since both real external services are critical to validating the behavior, this falls at the Workflow level where System and Agentic components interact.\n\nThe core failure mode—incoherent output or service breakdown on long audio files—can't be caught with mocks alone. Unit and Integration tests would pass with stubbed dependencies, but only real STT calls expose whet